dsDescriptionValue.value: Multiple rounds of Behavioral Tracking Survey were conducted in selected districts of Manipur and Nagalad under Avahan India's AIDS Initiative program in India. The main objective is to assess the impact of interventions on HIV risk behaviours in Manipur and Nagaland among  high risk population (eg. IDUs).  To assess changes in HIV risk behaviours the Behavioural Tracking Surveys (BTS) round two was undertaken among Injecting Drug Users (IDUs) in 2009.

fields.value:
The BTS is a cross sectional study and has used respondent driven sampling (RDS) to recruit adult male IDUs (18 years of age and above) from Ukhrul and Chandel districts in Manipur, and Kiphire and Zunheb
oto districts in Nagaland. RDS is a validated probability sampling method devised for use with hidden populations such as sex workers, men who have sex with men, and IDUs, that is based on social network theory and builds on conventional snowball sampling. It uses peer networks for recruitment of participants and involves payment of purposively recruited seed participants, who then refer other participants. The weights are designed to account for patterns of recruitment. For this study, a total sample of 1712 (Manipur=836 and Nagaland=876) were collected based on an ability to detect changes in proportions of 15% at follow-up surveys from estimated baseline values of 50% (which yield the biggest sample size), an alpha level of 0.05 for a two-sided test, and a power of 90%.
